00:00:12.590 --> 00:00:15.430
But before doing that,
various bits of feedback

00:00:15.430 --> 00:00:16.510
from office hours.

00:00:16.510 --> 00:00:17.850
Hearing from TAs.

00:00:17.850 --> 00:00:21.790
Getting a sense of where
the grand, gaping craters

00:00:21.790 --> 00:00:23.620
of confusion are so far.

00:00:23.620 --> 00:00:25.280
And apparently an
awful lot of them

00:00:25.280 --> 00:00:27.670
were provided in the
last two days of lectures

00:00:27.670 --> 00:00:28.860
with behavior genetics.

00:00:28.860 --> 00:00:30.640
Various issues that came up.

00:00:30.640 --> 00:00:33.830
Clearly, one of the most
complicated, inaccessible,

00:00:33.830 --> 00:00:35.450
subtle, pain in
the neck concepts

00:00:35.450 --> 00:00:38.420
in the whole class, which is
this heritability business.

00:00:38.420 --> 00:00:41.339
So memorize the
following two sentences,

00:00:41.339 --> 00:00:43.880
because it all comes down to
the difference between something

00:00:43.880 --> 00:00:48.750
that is inherited and
how heritable a trait is.

00:00:48.750 --> 00:00:51.510
The fact that humans
overwhelmingly

00:00:51.510 --> 00:00:54.840
have five fingers reflects the
fact that the number of fingers

00:00:54.840 --> 00:00:57.010
is an inherited trait.

00:00:57.010 --> 00:00:59.920
The fact that, when there are
some circumstances of humans

00:00:59.920 --> 00:01:01.880
having other than
five fingers, it

00:01:01.880 --> 00:01:04.510
is overwhelmingly
due to environmental

00:01:04.510 --> 00:01:07.040
something-or-others is
an indication of the fact

00:01:07.040 --> 00:01:11.770
that, nonetheless, variability
around the number of fingers--

00:01:11.770 --> 00:01:14.880
heritability is essentially 0%.

00:01:14.880 --> 00:01:16.610
So get those two
sorted out, and you

00:01:16.610 --> 00:01:19.390
have those two concepts
all under your belt

00:01:19.390 --> 00:01:21.170
and very useful.

00:01:21.170 --> 00:01:22.010
Why is it useful?

00:01:22.010 --> 00:01:23.890
First off, why is
this one useful?

00:01:23.890 --> 00:01:26.970
Because it is important
to know the distinction.

00:01:26.970 --> 00:01:29.360
Everybody, for one
thing, out there

00:01:29.360 --> 00:01:31.870
tends to view these as
telling the same thing.

00:01:31.870 --> 00:01:34.910
And insofar as they think
it says the same thing,

00:01:34.910 --> 00:01:38.370
they think that both terms
are referring to this.

00:01:38.370 --> 00:01:41.620
Something that is genetically
regulated, genetically

00:01:41.620 --> 00:01:43.020
determined-- whatever.

00:01:43.020 --> 00:01:44.330
Two totally different terms.

00:01:44.330 --> 00:01:46.500
So one reason to
obsess over this

00:01:46.500 --> 00:01:49.160
is that when the
newspapers give us

00:01:49.160 --> 00:01:51.900
our sound bite of
"scientists report that,"

00:01:51.900 --> 00:01:54.020
it's usually this one
that they're reporting,

00:01:54.020 --> 00:01:56.790
with one of those marvelously
misleading numbers.

00:01:56.790 --> 00:01:59.180
Which then sets people up
for thinking they have just

00:01:59.180 --> 00:02:02.340
been told how much
do genes "determine"

00:02:02.340 --> 00:02:04.300
some average feature
of this trait.

00:02:04.300 --> 00:02:05.850
So, important to
tell them apart.

00:02:05.850 --> 00:02:08.180
The other reason of
getting this sorted out

00:02:08.180 --> 00:02:10.610
is not to only unlearn
the nonsense aspects

00:02:10.610 --> 00:02:13.350
and misinterpreting this term
but because understanding

00:02:13.350 --> 00:02:15.570
that term gives you
a lot of insights

00:02:15.570 --> 00:02:17.600
into when and how
you are getting

00:02:17.600 --> 00:02:20.360
gene-environment interactions.

00:02:20.360 --> 00:02:21.400
Caveat with that.

00:02:21.400 --> 00:02:23.450
Saying "when and how
you're getting"--

00:02:23.450 --> 00:02:25.710
you're always getting
gene-environment interactions.

00:02:25.710 --> 00:02:27.380
Remember the quote
from the other day.

00:02:27.380 --> 00:02:29.250
It's like saying,
which contributes

00:02:29.250 --> 00:02:32.019
more to the volume of a square,
or the height, or the length,

00:02:32.019 --> 00:02:33.310
or the roundiness, or whatever?

00:02:33.310 --> 00:02:35.870
Yes, it's always
gene-environment interactions.

00:02:35.870 --> 00:02:37.880
Saying, in what
ways are there some

00:02:37.880 --> 00:02:41.140
of the more interesting ones,
dramatic ones, in what realms--

00:02:41.140 --> 00:02:44.670
Understand this, and you
avoid this confusion.

00:02:44.670 --> 00:02:46.120
Understand this,
and it gives you

00:02:46.120 --> 00:02:49.360
insights into
gene-environment interactions.

00:02:49.360 --> 00:02:49.860
OK.

00:02:49.860 --> 00:02:51.330
Other issues that are coming up.

00:02:51.330 --> 00:02:54.190
By now, we've looked at three
different broad approaches

00:02:54.190 --> 00:02:56.660
to the biology of
social behavior.

00:02:56.660 --> 00:02:59.105
The evolutionary stuff--
broadly stated-- the molecular,

00:02:59.105 --> 00:03:00.580
the behavior genetics.

00:03:00.580 --> 00:03:02.500
And what should
be clear by now is

00:03:02.500 --> 00:03:04.560
if you were living inside
one of those buckets,

00:03:04.560 --> 00:03:07.610
you hate each of the other
two and trash them entirely.

00:03:07.610 --> 00:03:10.820
So we get to the first of our
great, conflicting points,

00:03:10.820 --> 00:03:12.940
which is, does that mean
one of these is wrong?

00:03:12.940 --> 00:03:14.600
No, one of them is not wrong.

00:03:14.600 --> 00:03:15.600
None of them are wrong.

00:03:15.600 --> 00:03:18.130
Some are more right
than others, and some

00:03:18.130 --> 00:03:19.560
are a lot better than others.

00:03:19.560 --> 00:03:21.730
But nonetheless,
these are all-- again,

00:03:21.730 --> 00:03:24.060
from the very first
lecture-- different levels

00:03:24.060 --> 00:03:25.250
of description.

00:03:25.250 --> 00:03:28.230
Another way to begin to
think about this, in terms

00:03:28.230 --> 00:03:30.420
of what we've now
been focusing on--

00:03:30.420 --> 00:03:33.410
and this sort of coming up
from some questions afterward.

00:03:33.410 --> 00:03:36.230
So by now we've had
the term "epigenetics."

00:03:36.230 --> 00:03:38.450
That's come in in the
last couple of lectures.

00:03:38.450 --> 00:03:41.110
And there are at least
three different levels,

00:03:41.110 --> 00:03:44.280
three different buckets, with
which you can define the term.

00:03:44.280 --> 00:03:45.850
What is epigenetics?

00:03:45.850 --> 00:03:48.840
Epigenetics is the way
the culture, environment--

00:03:48.840 --> 00:03:52.000
all of that-- affects biology.

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:54.090
That's a certain broad
way of stating that.

00:03:54.090 --> 00:03:55.950
NodA stated that
way, you are making

00:03:55.950 --> 00:03:59.090
biology synonymous with
genetics, which ain't so.

00:03:59.090 --> 00:04:01.340
But nonetheless, that's
a certain broad level

00:04:01.340 --> 00:04:02.270
of stating it.

00:04:02.270 --> 00:04:04.720
In another discipline,
a very sort

00:04:04.720 --> 00:04:06.990
of first pass at
molecular stuff,

00:04:06.990 --> 00:04:08.640
what is epigenetics about?

00:04:08.640 --> 00:04:11.710
It's the way in which
environments turns genes

00:04:11.710 --> 00:04:13.690
on and off.

00:04:13.690 --> 00:04:16.640
And at another level of
explanation, more reductive,

00:04:16.640 --> 00:04:18.430
what is epigenetics about?

00:04:18.430 --> 00:04:22.860
It is regulation of chromatin
remodeling and methylation

00:04:22.860 --> 00:04:24.360
of genes and all of that.

00:04:24.360 --> 00:04:26.040
Do not panic, if
that's not the level

00:04:26.040 --> 00:04:27.200
you want to know it about.

00:04:27.200 --> 00:04:28.825
That's the business
from the other day,

00:04:28.825 --> 00:04:32.640
about changing access
of transcription factors

00:04:32.640 --> 00:04:34.510
to DNA-- jargony
way of doing it.

00:04:34.510 --> 00:04:35.010
Don't worry.

00:04:35.010 --> 00:04:38.170
The main point being that this
is a completely different level

00:04:38.170 --> 00:04:40.240
of defining this.

00:04:40.240 --> 00:04:41.650
This is the whole point in here.

00:04:41.650 --> 00:04:44.310
We are beginning to see
different disciplinary

00:04:44.310 --> 00:04:45.030
approaches.

00:04:45.030 --> 00:04:47.930
We are beginning to see where
one discipline has decided

00:04:47.930 --> 00:04:49.620
they have answered a question.

00:04:49.620 --> 00:04:52.190
This is how culture
affects biology?

00:04:52.190 --> 00:04:53.310
Give me a break.

00:04:53.310 --> 00:04:55.850
Show me which genes
we're talking about!

00:04:55.850 --> 00:04:57.240
We're talking about genes, here.

00:04:57.240 --> 00:04:58.220
Give me a break.

00:04:58.220 --> 00:05:00.800
Show me-- is this chromatin
remodeling-- what's

00:05:00.800 --> 00:05:01.740
the mechanism for it?

00:05:01.740 --> 00:05:03.190
How reversible is it?

00:05:03.190 --> 00:05:06.030
One discipline's answer is the
next one's starting point--

00:05:06.030 --> 00:05:06.690
blah, blah.

00:05:06.690 --> 00:05:10.250
One discipline's wonderfully
satisfying scientific answer

00:05:10.250 --> 00:05:11.830
is the basis for
the next discipline

00:05:11.830 --> 00:05:13.630
to be totally
contemptuous of them.

00:05:13.630 --> 00:05:15.200
You call that science?

00:05:15.200 --> 00:05:16.830
This is sort of the
whole point, here,

00:05:16.830 --> 00:05:20.650
beginning to see how we could
chip out a way between these.

00:05:20.650 --> 00:05:23.070
More bits of clarification.

00:05:23.070 --> 00:05:25.940
Amid that, one of the things
that really came through

00:05:25.940 --> 00:05:28.030
is-- in the sort of
ratio of praising

00:05:28.030 --> 00:05:31.520
to trashing-- I was clearly
spending a lot of the last two

00:05:31.520 --> 00:05:34.230
days trashing the
behavior-genetics approaches.

00:05:34.230 --> 00:05:36.430
So a little bit of
clarification, there.

00:05:36.430 --> 00:05:38.510
First off, we can
broadly divide what

00:05:38.510 --> 00:05:42.190
came the last two days into
classical behavior genetics.

00:05:42.190 --> 00:05:45.800
And that's the comparing
monozygotic and dizygotic

00:05:45.800 --> 00:05:46.730
twins.

00:05:46.730 --> 00:05:48.870
That's the adoption
studies, that's

00:05:48.870 --> 00:05:52.400
the twins adopted at birth--
that's all of those approaches,

00:05:52.400 --> 00:05:53.020
there.

00:05:53.020 --> 00:05:56.430
Those are all the ones where
you were just inferring really

00:05:56.430 --> 00:05:58.860
indirectly that there's
something genetically going

00:05:58.860 --> 00:05:59.670
on there.

00:05:59.670 --> 00:06:02.470
The other half, and much more
sort of the modern behavior

00:06:02.470 --> 00:06:05.900
genetics, is marrying these
traditional approaches

00:06:05.900 --> 00:06:07.810
with molecular biology.

00:06:07.810 --> 00:06:11.390
And that was the business at
the end-- you know the gene,

00:06:11.390 --> 00:06:14.030
and you kind of have an
idea of what it might do.

00:06:14.030 --> 00:06:16.590
How does that map onto
behavioral variability

00:06:16.590 --> 00:06:17.590
in humans?

00:06:17.590 --> 00:06:19.320
You know the
behavior, and you've

00:06:19.320 --> 00:06:21.650
got some sense of
its variability.

00:06:21.650 --> 00:06:24.410
How does that map onto
variability in genes?

00:06:24.410 --> 00:06:27.470
This is the much more powerful,
contemporary end of it.

00:06:27.470 --> 00:06:29.330
So what is this end good for?

00:06:29.330 --> 00:06:32.380
All it's good for is pronouncing
that something's genetic,

00:06:32.380 --> 00:06:35.330
or it's 73% genetic
and then you trash it

00:06:35.330 --> 00:06:36.570
because that's jibberish.

00:06:36.570 --> 00:06:38.200
What it's good for mainly is--

00:06:38.200 --> 00:06:40.080
OK, so you've got
an adoption study--

00:06:40.080 --> 00:06:42.920
classical
behavior-genetic study--

00:06:42.920 --> 00:06:46.370
where they're adopted right
at birth, within seconds,

00:06:46.370 --> 00:06:48.050
and raised in
different households.

00:06:48.050 --> 00:06:50.020
Oh, you haven't ruled
out environment!

00:06:50.020 --> 00:06:51.690
Don't forget
prenatal environment.

00:06:51.690 --> 00:06:53.310
Oh, you haven't ruled
out environment!

00:06:53.310 --> 00:06:55.280
Remember the
nonrandom assignment

00:06:55.280 --> 00:06:56.580
of adoption-- all of that.

00:06:56.580 --> 00:06:58.410
Does this mean this
approach is useless?

00:06:58.410 --> 00:06:58.910
No.

00:06:58.910 --> 00:07:01.880
What it's good for is
demonstrating nonetheless well

00:07:01.880 --> 00:07:05.770
we've just ruled out all
sorts of realms of environment

00:07:05.770 --> 00:07:08.250
that people would
guess is consequential.

00:07:08.250 --> 00:07:10.340
It's less consequential
than you think.

00:07:10.340 --> 00:07:13.350
We haven't ruled out
environment entirely.

00:07:13.350 --> 00:07:16.080
And just because it's all
gene-environment interaction,

00:07:16.080 --> 00:07:18.910
we certainly can't come up
with a stupid number like that.

00:07:18.910 --> 00:07:21.370
But what this is good
for is at least showing,

00:07:21.370 --> 00:07:23.920
here's domains where
people-- a lot of people--

00:07:23.920 --> 00:07:27.920
would have assumed there is
big environmental effects.

00:07:27.920 --> 00:07:29.470
Much less than you would think.

00:07:29.470 --> 00:07:31.360
So that's the much
more conservative, sort

00:07:31.360 --> 00:07:33.850
of sobrietous thing that
people can do with that field.

00:07:33.850 --> 00:07:36.120
The fact that far too
few of them actually

00:07:36.120 --> 00:07:39.500
do that is reasons to trash--
no, well, nonetheless, there's

00:07:39.500 --> 00:07:41.330
lots of good things
in behavior genetics.

00:07:41.330 --> 00:07:44.010
But that's the limited
domain where it's useful.

00:07:44.010 --> 00:07:46.310
OK, so just beginning
to get a sense, here,

00:07:46.310 --> 00:07:49.060
